me":1759167326464,"parent_id":"27da8836-e820-80dd-8e91-fd26f5fc0a25","parent_table":"block","alive":true,"created_by_table":"notion_user","created_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925","last_edited_by_table":"notion_user","last_edited_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925"},"role":"editor"}},"27da8836-e820-8013-87ff-c8182aac2942":{"spaceId":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","value":{"value":{"id":"27da8836-e820-8013-87ff-c8182aac2942","space_id":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","version":3,"type":"text","properties":{"title":[["In Part 3, McSpadden reflects on the aftermath of her son Michael Brown’s death and the way the Ferguson community and the wider nation responded. She emphasizes how personal grief collided with public protest. The section highlights the ways in which her family’s mourning was continually interrupted by the national spotlight, media attention, and the criminal justice process. McSpadden insists that the pain of losing a child was compounded by a lack of accountability from authorities, who treated her son not as a victim but as a suspect even in death. She also grapples with the symbolic meaning Michael’s death took on—her son became a rallying point for the struggle against police violence, but this transformation came with the painful trade-off of her private loss being made public. Part 3 illustrates both her resilience and the broader demand for systemic change, while also underlining how Black mothers bear the unique weight of losing children to state violence."]]},"crdt_data":{"title":{"r":"PLKzR2dZSc3s2sKuf_rscA,\"start\",\"end\"","n":{"PLKzR2dZSc3s2sKuf_rscA,\"start\",\"end\"":{"s":{"x":"PLKzR2dZSc3s2sKuf_rscA","i":[{"t":"s"},{"t":"t","i":["n5Fp4kEs46z1",1],"o":"start","l":980,"c":"In Part 3, McSpadden reflects on the aftermath of her son Michael Brown’s death and the way the Ferguson community and the wider nation responded. She emphasizes how personal grief collided with public protest. The section highlights the ways in which her family’s mourning was continually interrupted by the national spotlight, media attention, and the criminal justice process. McSpadden insists that the pain of losing a child was compounded by a lack of accountability from authorities, who treated her son not as a victim but as a suspect even in death. She also grapples with the symbolic meaning Michael’s death took on—her son became a rallying point for the struggle against police violence, but this transformation came with the painful trade-off of her private loss being made public. Part 3 illustrates both her resilience and the broader demand for systemic change, while also underlining how Black mothers bear the unique weight of losing children to state violence."},{"t":"e"}],"l":""},"c":[]}}}},"crdt_format_version":1,"created_time":1759167326455,"last_edited_time":1759167326464,"parent_id":"27da8836-e820-80dd-8e91-fd26f5fc0a25","parent_table":"block","alive":true,"created_by_table":"notion_user","created_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925","last_edited_by_table":"notion_user","last_edited_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925"},"role":"editor"}},"27da8836-e820-80ad-a8d5-d259c857fff1":{"spaceId":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","value":{"value":{"id":"27da8836-e820-80ad-a8d5-d259c857fff1","space_id":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","version":2,"type":"divider","crdt_data":{"title":{"r":"Ski8jE3-snVg4TmChB8hdw,\"start\",\"end\"","n":{"Ski8jE3-snVg4TmChB8hdw,\"start\",\"end\"":{"s":{"x":"Ski8jE3-snVg4TmChB8hdw","i":[{"t":"s"},{"t":"e"}],"l":""},"c":[]}}}},"crdt_format_version":1,"created_time":1759167326456,"last_edited_time":1759167326464,"parent_id":"27da8836-e820-80dd-8e91-fd26f5fc0a25","parent_table":"block","alive":true,"created_by_table":"notion_user","created_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925","last_edited_by_table":"notion_user","last_edited_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925"},"role":"editor"}},"27da8836-e820-80df-ae6b-e860ddec8618":{"spaceId":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","value":{"value":{"id":"27da8836-e820-80df-ae6b-e860ddec8618","space_id":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","version":4,"type":"sub_sub_header","properties":{"title":[["Jelani Cobb, "],["“What I Saw in Ferguson”",[["i"]]],[" (Aug. 14, 2014)"]]},"crdt_data":{"title":{"r":"Gll4tf9tJDNtsfst4J8TVA,\"start\",\"end\"","n":{"Gll4tf9tJDNtsfst4J8TVA,\"start\",\"end\"":{"s":{"x":"Gll4tf9tJDNtsfst4J8TVA","i":[{"t":"s"},{"t":"t","i":["A2OCiwOhrbCW",1],"o":"start","l":13,"c":"Jelani Cobb, "},{"t":"t","i":["A2OCiwOhrbCW",14],"o":["A2OCiwOhrbCW",13],"l":24,"c":"“What I Saw in Ferguson”","b":[{"t":"a","x":"Gll4tf9tJDNtsfst4J8TVA","l":"","i":["A2OCiwOhrbCW",54],"s":{"i":["A2OCiwOhrbCW",14],"a":"b"},"e":{"i":["A2OCiwOhrbCW",38],"a":"b"},"a":["i"]}]},{"t":"t","i":["A2OCiwOhrbCW",38],"o":["A2OCiwOhrbCW",37],"l":16,"c":" (Aug. 14, 2014)","b":[]},{"t":"e"}],"l":""},"c":[]}}}},"crdt_format_version":1,"created_time":1759167326457,"last_edited_time":1759167326464,"parent_id":"27da8836-e820-80dd-8e91-fd26f5fc0a25","parent_table":"block","alive":true,"created_by_table":"notion_user","created_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925","last_edited_by_table":"notion_user","last_edited_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925"},"role":"editor"}},"27da8836-e820-80c8-bb65-d20d762203ab":{"spaceId":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","value":{"value":{"id":"27da8836-e820-80c8-bb65-d20d762203ab","space_id":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","version":3,"type":"text","properties":{"title":[["Cobb offers a first-hand account of arriving in Ferguson in the immediate days after Michael Brown’s killing. He describes the city as tense, overwhelmed by heavy police presence, and marked by clear racial divides. One of Cobb’s key observations is how the militarized police response transformed peaceful demonstrations into confrontational encounters. He notes that residents’ anger was not only about Brown’s death but also about years of accumulated frustration with systemic racism, economic neglect, and abusive policing. Cobb critiques the authorities’ failure to build trust, pointing to their use of riot gear, tear gas, and curfews as strategies that escalated rather than calmed the situation. He also captures the humanity of the protesters, who gathered not only in anger but also in grief and solidarity. The essay situates Ferguson within the longer history of racial inequality in America, suggesting that the uprising was both a local eruption and part of a broader national reckoning with race and policing."]]},"crdt_data":{"title":{"r":"HCvDUFaZJG2qQaWhINJKbA,\"start\",\"end\"","n":{"HCvDUFaZJG2qQaWhINJKbA,\"start\",\"end\"":{"s":{"x":"HCvDUFaZJG2qQaWhINJKbA","i":[{"t":"s"},{"t":"t","i":["1bZhG51x5m7K",1],"o":"start","l":1026,"c":"Cobb offers a first-hand account of arriving in Ferguson in the immediate days after Michael Brown’s killing. He describes the city as tense, overwhelmed by heavy police presence, and marked by clear racial divides. One of Cobb’s key observations is how the militarized police response transformed peaceful demonstrations into confrontational encounters. He notes that residents’ anger was not only about Brown’s death but also about years of accumulated frustration with systemic racism, economic neglect, and abusive policing. Cobb critiques the authorities’ failure to build trust, pointing to their use of riot gear, tear gas, and curfews as strategies that escalated rather than calmed the situation. He also captures the humanity of the protesters, who gathered not only in anger but also in grief and solidarity. The essay situates Ferguson within the longer history of racial inequality in America, suggesting that the uprising was both a local eruption and part of a broader national reckoning with race and policing."},{"t":"e"}],"l":""},"c":[]}}}},"crdt_format_version":1,"created_time":1759167326458,"last_edited_time":1759167326464,"parent_id":"27da8836-e820-80dd-8e91-fd26f5fc0a25"